# ERP Boilerplate — Cursor Rules

Node + Express + Prisma + PostgreSQL

These rules are the single source of truth for every decision made in this codebase. Read them fully before generating or modifying any file.

## 1. Prime Directive

This is a production-grade ERP backend boilerplate.
Every decision prioritises: correctness → security → readability → cleverness.
Boring and deterministic is the feature. Do NOT be creative with architecture.
When in doubt, follow the existing pattern exactly — this is a template others will clone, so consistency is more important than local optimisation.

## 2. Language & Runtime

- TypeScript strict mode only. No `any`. No `as unknown as X` casts.
- Target: Node 20 LTS, ESNext modules compiled to CommonJS via tsc.
- Use `tsx` for dev execution (`tsx watch src/server.ts`).
- All files use `.ts` extension. No `.js` files in src/.
- Enable: strict, noUncheckedIndexedAccess, exactOptionalPropertyTypes in tsconfig.
- Imports: named imports preferred. No default exports except in `*.routes.ts` files.
- Path aliases: `@/*` maps to `src/*`. Use them everywhere.

## 3. Folder Architecture — Non-Negotiable

```
src/
  app.ts                          ← Express app factory, middleware stack, route mounts
  server.ts                       ← HTTP server bootstrap only (listen, signals)

  features/
    {feature}/
      {feature}.routes.ts         ← Express Router, ONLY mounts handlers + middleware
      {feature}.controller.ts     ← req/res boundary. Calls service. Returns envelope.
      {feature}.service.ts        ← Business logic. No req/res. No Prisma directly.
      {feature}.queries.ts        ← ALL Prisma calls live here and ONLY here.
      {feature}.schema.ts         ← Zod schemas for request validation
      {feature}.types.ts          ← Feature-local interfaces and type aliases
      {feature}.middleware.ts     ← Feature-specific middleware (optional)

  shared/
    middleware/
      authenticate.ts             ← JWT verification → attaches req.user
      authorize.ts                ← RBAC check factory: authorize('resource', 'action')
      validate.ts                 ← Zod schema validation middleware factory
      rateLimiter.ts              ← express-rate-limit configurations
      requestId.ts                ← attaches x-request-id to every request
      errorHandler.ts             ← universal error handler (last middleware)
      notFound.ts                 ← 404 catch-all

    lib/
      prisma.ts                   ← PrismaClient singleton
      logger.ts                   ← Pino logger singleton
      jwt.ts                      ← sign/verify token helpers
      password.ts                 ← hash/compare helpers (bcryptjs)
      response.ts                 ← sendSuccess / sendError envelope builders
      paginate.ts                 ← offset pagination utility
      audit.ts                    ← Prisma middleware for audit trail

    types/
      express.d.ts                ← Augment Express Request with req.user, req.id
      common.ts                   ← Shared types: ApiResponse, PaginatedResult, etc.

    constants/
      roles.ts                    ← Role and Permission seed constants
      errors.ts                   ← AppError class + HTTP error factories

  config/
    env.ts                        ← Zod-parsed, typed env (throws on startup if invalid)

prisma/
  schema.prisma
  seed.ts
  migrations/

docker/
  Dockerfile
  docker-compose.yml
  .dockerignore
```

**Rules:**

- NEVER import Prisma client outside of `*.queries.ts` files.
- NEVER put business logic in a controller.
- NEVER put req/res types in a service.
- NEVER create a file that doesn't fit this structure. Ask first.
- NEVER create a `utils/` folder. Find the correct `shared/` location.
- NEVER create a `helpers/` folder. Same reason.

## 4. Naming Conventions

| Kind | Convention | Example |
|------|------------|---------|
| Files | kebab-case (except feature files) | auth-token.ts, rate-limiter.ts |
| Feature files | `{feature}.{layer}.ts` | users.routes.ts, users.service.ts |
| Classes | PascalCase | AppError, TokenService |
| Interfaces | PascalCase + I | IUser, ITokenPayload (types files only) |
| Types | PascalCase | ApiResponse\<T\>, PaginatedResult\<T\> |
| Functions | camelCase | findUserById, hashPassword |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE | JWT_SECRET, DEFAULT_ROLE |
| Zod schemas | camelCase + Schema | createUserSchema, loginSchema |
| Route files | feature.routes.ts | users.routes.ts, auth.routes.ts |
| Prisma models | PascalCase | User, Organization, AuditLog |
| DB columns | camelCase (Prisma default) | |
| ENV vars | SCREAMING_SNAKE | |

## 5. API Response Envelope — Always Use This Shape

Every single route response must use the envelope. Never call `res.json()` directly in a controller. Always use `sendSuccess()` or `sendError()` from `shared/lib/response.ts`.

**Success:**

```json
{
  "success": true,
  "data": "<T>",
  "meta": {
    "page": 1,
    "limit": 20,
    "total": 100,
    "totalPages": 5
  }
}
```

(`meta` omitted if not paginated)

**Error:**

```json
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
    "message": "Human message",
    "details": []
  }
}
```

**HTTP status codes:**

- 200 → GET success, UPDATE success
- 201 → CREATE success
- 204 → DELETE success (no body)
- 400 → Validation error
- 401 → Not authenticated
- 403 → Not authorised (authenticated but forbidden)
- 404 → Not found
- 409 → Conflict (duplicate)
- 422 → Unprocessable entity
- 429 → Rate limited
- 500 → Unhandled server error

## 6. Error Handling

- ALL errors flow through the universal `errorHandler` middleware. No exceptions.
- Throw `AppError` instances from services and queries. Never throw raw Errors.
- Never catch-and-swallow errors. Re-throw with context or let them bubble.
- Never expose stack traces, Prisma internals, or SQL in responses.
- Log the full error (including stack) in the error handler, not at throw site.
- Prisma error codes (P2002, P2025, etc.) must be mapped to AppError in queries layer.

**AppError signature:**

```typescript
new AppError(message: string, statusCode: number, code: string, details?: unknown)
```

**Common factory helpers in `shared/constants/errors.ts`:**

- `notFound(resource: string)`
- `unauthorized(message?)`
- `forbidden(message?)`
- `conflict(field: string)`
- `validationError(details)`
- `internal(message?)`

## 7. Authentication & Sessions

- Access token: JWT, short-lived (15m), signed with HS256, contains `{ sub, role, organizationId }`
- Refresh token: opaque UUID, stored in DB (Session table), 7-day expiry
- Refresh token rotation: each use issues a new token and invalidates the old one
- Token blacklist: revoked JTIs stored in `Session.revokedAt` column
- `authenticate` middleware: verifies access token → attaches `req.user = { id, role, organizationId }`
- All protected routes MUST use `authenticate` middleware
- Passwords: bcryptjs, saltRounds = 12
- Never log tokens, passwords, or PII

## 8. RBAC — Resource + Action Model

Authorization is always: role → resource → action.
Never hardcode role checks. Always use the `authorize()` middleware factory.

**Actions (exhaustive list, use only these):**

`'create' | 'read' | 'update' | 'delete' | 'export'`

**Usage in routes:**

```typescript
router.get('/', authenticate, authorize('products', 'read'), controller.list)
router.post('/', authenticate, authorize('products', 'create'), controller.create)
```

`authorize()` resolves permissions from DB at request time (cached per process).
Permissions are seeded via `prisma/seed.ts`. Adding a new permission = new seed row, no code change.

**Permission table structure:**

`Permission { id, roleId, resource: string, action: Action }`

**Built-in roles (seeded, not hardcoded):**

- SUPER_ADMIN → all resources, all actions
- ADMIN → all resources, all actions except system config
- MANAGER → read/create/update on operational resources
- EMPLOYEE → read-only on own-organization resources
- VIEWER → read-only, global

## 9. Prisma Rules

- ONE PrismaClient instance. Singleton in `shared/lib/prisma.ts`. Import only in `*.queries.ts`.
- Every model MUST have: id (cuid), createdAt, updatedAt, deletedAt (soft delete).
- Soft delete: NEVER use `prisma.model.delete()`. Use `updateMany({ deletedAt: new Date() })`.
- All queries MUST filter: `where: { deletedAt: null }` unless explicitly fetching deleted.
- Optimistic locking: add `version Int @default(0)` to any model edited concurrently.
- Audit middleware: attach in `shared/lib/audit.ts`, registered in `shared/lib/prisma.ts`.
- Multi-tenancy: every non-auth model MUST have `organizationId` field.
- Relations: always define both sides. Always name relation fields explicitly.
- Never use `prisma.$queryRaw` unless absolutely unavoidable. Document why if used.
- Migrations: NEVER edit migration files after they're created.
- Select fields explicitly in queries. Never return full Prisma model to controller.

**Schema conventions:**

```prisma
model User {
  id             String    @id @default(cuid())
  createdAt      DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt      DateTime  @updatedAt
  deletedAt      DateTime?
  version        Int       @default(0)
  organizationId String
  organization   Organization @relation(fields: [organizationId], references: [id])
}
```

## 10. Validation

- Zod is the ONLY validation library. No express-validator. No joi.
- Every route with a body, params, or query MUST use the `validate()` middleware.
- Schemas live in `{feature}.schema.ts`. Export named: `createUserSchema`, `updateUserSchema`, etc.
- `validate()` middleware factory signature: `validate(schema, target: 'body'|'params'|'query')`
- Strip unknown fields: use `.strict()` on body schemas.
- Never validate inside a controller or service. Validation happens at the route level.

## 11. Logging

- Pino for all logging. One singleton in `shared/lib/logger.ts`.
- Log levels: error (5xx), warn (4xx, suspicious), info (lifecycle events), debug (dev only).
- Every log entry MUST include: requestId, userId (if available), feature, action.
- NEVER log: passwords, tokens, full request bodies containing PII, credit card data.
- Request log format: `{ requestId, method, path, statusCode, responseTimeMs, userId? }`
- Error log format: `{ requestId, error.message, error.stack, error.code, userId? }`
- In production: JSON format. In development: pino-pretty.

## 12. Environment & Config

ALL environment variables are parsed and validated at startup in `config/env.ts` using Zod.
If any required var is missing, the process exits with a descriptive error before binding.
Never access `process.env` directly outside of `config/env.ts`.
Import: `import { env } from '@/config/env'`

**Required vars (documented in `.env.example`):**

- DATABASE_URL
- JWT_SECRET (min 32 chars)
- JWT_REFRESH_SECRET (min 32 chars)
- JWT_ACCESS_EXPIRES (e.g. "15m")
- JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRES (e.g. "7d")
- PORT (default 3000)
- NODE_ENV (development | production | test)
- BCRYPT_SALT_ROUNDS (default 12)
- RATE_LIMIT_WINDOW_MS (default 900000)
- RATE_LIMIT_MAX (default 100)
- LOG_LEVEL (default "info")

## 13. Rate Limiting

Three separate rate limiters (configured in `shared/middleware/rateLimiter.ts`):

- `globalLimiter` → all routes, 100 req/15min
- `authLimiter` → /auth routes only, 10 req/15min (stricter)
- `loginLimiter` → POST /auth/login only, 5 req/15min (strictest)

**Per-user login lockout (not rate-limit based):**

- Track failed login attempts in User model: `failedLoginAttempts`, `lockedUntil`
- Lock for 15 minutes after 5 consecutive failures.
- Reset counter on successful login.

## 14. Controller Pattern — Copy This Exactly

```typescript
// users.controller.ts
import { RequestHandler } from 'express'
import { sendSuccess } from '@/shared/lib/response'
import * as usersService from './users.service'

export const list: RequestHandler = async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const result = await usersService.listUsers(req.query, req.user!)
    sendSuccess(res, result.data, 200, result.meta)
  } catch (error) {
    next(error)  // ← ALWAYS pass to next(). Never handle in controller.
  }
}

export const create: RequestHandler = async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const user = await usersService.createUser(req.body, req.user!)
    sendSuccess(res, user, 201)
  } catch (error) {
    next(error)
  }
}
```

## 15. Service Pattern

```typescript
// users.service.ts
// - No imports from express. No req, res, next.
// - Receives plain typed params, returns plain typed values.
// - Calls queries. Contains all business logic.
// - Throws AppError for expected failures.

import * as usersQueries from './users.queries'
import { notFound, conflict } from '@/shared/constants/errors'
import type { ITokenUser } from '@/shared/types/common'

export async function createUser(dto: CreateUserDto, actor: ITokenUser) {
  const existing = await usersQueries.findByEmail(dto.email)
  if (existing) throw conflict('email')
  return usersQueries.createUser(dto)
}
```

## 16. Routes Pattern — Copy This Exactly

```typescript
// users.routes.ts
import { Router } from 'express'
import { authenticate } from '@/shared/middleware/authenticate'
import { authorize } from '@/shared/middleware/authorize'
import { validate } from '@/shared/middleware/validate'
import { createUserSchema, updateUserSchema } from './users.schema'
import * as controller from './users.controller'

const router = Router()

router.get('/',
  authenticate,
  authorize('users', 'read'),
  controller.list
)

router.get('/:id',
  authenticate,
  authorize('users', 'read'),
  controller.getById
)

router.post('/',
  authenticate,
  authorize('users', 'create'),
  validate(createUserSchema, 'body'),
  controller.create
)

router.patch('/:id',
  authenticate,
  authorize('users', 'update'),
  validate(updateUserSchema, 'body'),
  controller.update
)

router.delete('/:id',
  authenticate,
  authorize('users', 'delete'),
  controller.remove
)

export default router
```

## 17. What Never To Do

NEVER:

- Use `any` type
- Import PrismaClient outside `*.queries.ts`
- Call `res.json()` directly in a controller
- Catch and swallow errors silently
- Put business logic in a route handler
- Put Prisma calls in a controller or service
- Hardcode roles or permissions in code
- Use `.delete()` in Prisma (soft-delete only)
- Forget `deletedAt: null` in where clauses
- Forget `organizationId` on non-auth models
- Use `console.log` (use logger)
- Create a catch-all `/api/...` route
- Merge routes from different features into one file
- Skip the `validate()` middleware on any mutating route
- Expose internal error details to the client
- Create any folder not defined in section 3
- Skip the response envelope
- Return Prisma model objects directly (select fields explicitly)

## 18. Dependency Rules

**Allowed production dependencies (no others without explicit user approval):**

- express → HTTP framework
- @prisma/client → ORM
- zod → validation
- bcryptjs → password hashing
- jsonwebtoken → JWT
- helmet → security headers
- cors → CORS
- express-rate-limit → rate limiting
- pino → logging
- pino-pretty → dev log formatting
- uuid → UUIDs for request IDs, refresh tokens
- dotenv → env loading in dev

**Allowed dev dependencies:**

- prisma, typescript, tsx
- @types/express, @types/bcryptjs, @types/jsonwebtoken, @types/node, @types/cors, @types/uuid

**Do NOT add:** lodash, moment, dayjs, axios, class-validator, class-transformer, typeorm, sequelize, mongoose, passport, express-jwt, or any test framework.

## 19. Git & Template Hygiene

- `.env` is always gitignored. `.env.example` is always committed.
- `.gitignore` must cover: node_modules, dist, .env, *.log, .DS_Store
- Every TODO in comments is formatted: `// TODO(template): description`
- `prisma/seed.ts` must be idempotent (upsert, not insert)
- README.md must contain: quickstart, env var table, seed instructions, architecture explanation, how to add a new feature slice
- CLAUDE.md or AGENTS.md must contain these rules in summary form for any AI agent working on derivative projects

## 20. Scope Guard

This is a BOILERPLATE / TEMPLATE. It demonstrates patterns, not business logic.
When generating example features (products, inventory, etc.):

- Keep data models realistic but minimal
- Comment every non-obvious decision with `// WHY: explanation`
- Mark extension points with `// TODO(template): add your X logic here`
- Do not implement real business rules — implement the SHAPE of business rules

The goal: a developer clones this, reads the code for 30 minutes, and knows exactly how to add any new feature without asking anyone.
